Predictive Policing in Chicago, IL

Chris Michael

October 20, 2022

A. Introduction

The Purpose of Predictive Policing

Predictive Policing is a step towards reducing policing bias, brutality and unwarranted surveillance within communities. This concept becomes increasing important particularly in a time where the country has been experiencing a surge in weapons related violence. This study aims to understand the relationships between weapons violations and spatial variables, to predict future crime hotspots in the city of Chicago. It is important to note however, that crime is heavily dependent on numerous other externalities that is beyond the scope of study at this time. This model can be a useful tool that could serve as a base model for future predictive policing for cities in the U.S.

C. Chicago Crime Data

I. Reading the Data

I used the socrata package for pulling data. The reason I chose weapons violations as the type of crime I wanted to take a closer look at is because of the increasing number of weapons related violent crime that has been occuring in the U.S. Coming from a country with stringent weapon control laws, it was interesting to study the relationship between weapons violations and spatial variables.

policeDistricts <-

  st_transform('ESRI:102271') %>%
  dplyr::select(District = dist_num)

D. Investigating Risk Factors

I. Pulling Risk Factor Data

In order to investigate the relationship of weapons violations to spatial features, I utilized data from the Chicago Open Data Portal. The spatial risk factors include police stations, fire stations, grocery stores, liquor retail stores, places without functional street lights and abandoned buildings. These variables were chosen based on the assumption that their proximity could potentially have an effect on weapons related crime.

PoliceStations <- 
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/z8bn-74gv.json") %>%
  dplyr::select(Y = latitude, X = longitude) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
    st_transform(st_crs(fishnet)) %>%
    mutate(Legend = "Police Stations")

D. Feature Engineering

I. Risk Factors by Fishnet

The maps below shows the clustering of the risk factors for each fishnet cell. This is later useful for aggregation by k nearest neighbor and other spatial functions. This row of maps shows the density of spatial features.

st_c <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid

vars_net <- 
  rbind(PoliceStations, GroceryStores, FireStations, LiquorRetail, 
        StreetLightsOut, AbandonBuildings) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
    full_join(fishnet) %>%
    spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    ungroup()

vars_net.long <- 
  gather(vars_net, Variable, value, -geometry, -uniqueID)

vars <- unique(vars_net.long$Variable)
mapList <- list()

for(i in vars)
  mapList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(vars_net.long, Variable == i), aes(fill=value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_gradientn(colors=pal, name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      theme_void() 

do.call(ggarrange,c(mapList))

II. K Nearest Neighbor

In this section, the k-nearest-neighbor function is used to find the spatial distribution of the risk factors (from the previous section), to calculate the average distance from the closest 3 incident of assaults to the various spatial features listed above. These row of maps shows the average distance to the spatial features.

vars_net <- vars_net %>%
    dplyr::mutate(PoliceStations.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(PoliceStations),
                                           k = 3),
           GroceryStores.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(GroceryStores),
                                           k = 3),
           FireStations.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(FireStations),
                                           k = 3),
           LiquorRetail.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(LiquorRetail),
                                           k = 3),
           StreetLightsOut.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(StreetLightsOut),
                                           k = 3),
           AbandonBuildings.nn = nn_function(st_c(st_coid(vars_net)), 
                                           st_c(AbandonBuildings),
                                           k = 3)) 
vars_net1 <- vars_net %>%

E. Spatial Processes

I. Local Morans I Statistic

The Local Morans I Statistic is calculated for weapons violations in Chicago. The Morans I statistics is near 30% towards the west of Chicago which suggests some positive spatial autocorrelation, or clustering of weapons violation crimes.The p-value suggest that weapons violations cluster more than what is expected due to random chance alone. The significant hotspot maps suggests that there is more than one occurrence of clustering of hotspots around the city.

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)

final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countWeaponsVio, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(WeaponsVioCount = countWeaponsVio, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_gradientn(colors=pal) +
      labs(title=i) +
      theme_void()}

do.call(ggarrange,c(varList))

F. Cross Validation & Regressions

I. Poisson Regression

In this section, the cross validated poisson regression is used to test generalizability, to see how well the model performs in other areas. To test this, two methods are used: the k-fold technique and the LOGO-CV technique.

reg.vars <- c("PoliceStations.nn","GroceryStores.nn","FireStations.nn",
              "LiquorRetail.nn","StreetLightsOut.nn","AbandonBuildings.nn")

reg.ss.vars <- c("PoliceStations.nn","GroceryStores.nn","FireStations.nn",
                 "LiquorRetail.nn","StreetLightsOut.nn","AbandonBuildings.nn", 
                 "weaponsvio.isSig", "weaponsvio.isSig.dist")

reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeaponsVio",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeaponsVio, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeaponsVio",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeaponsVio, Prediction, geometry)

reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeaponsVio",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeaponsVio, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeaponsVio",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeaponsVio, Prediction, geometry)

reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv, Error = Prediction - countWeaponsVio,
           Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    mutate(reg.ss.cv, Error = Prediction - countWeaponsVio,
           Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    mutate(reg.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countWeaponsVio,
           Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countWeaponsVio,
           Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
    st_sf() 

error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countWeaponsVio, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  ggplot(aes(MAE)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 50, colour="black", fill = "#bdc367") +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +  
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 8, by = 1)) + 
    labs(title="Distribution of MAE", subtitle = "k-fold cross validation vs. LOGO-CV",
         x="Mean Absolute Error", y="Count") +
    theme_minimal()

The series of histograms shown above indicate that the models using the k-fold cross validation method are generally more accurate that the models using the LOGO-CV technique. In both sets (random k-fold and LOGO-CV), the model is significantly improved by adding spatial features (distance to the hotspots). The lowest Mean Absolute Error (MAE) is 0.42 which is the model that uses random k-fold and spatial processes.

st_drop_geometry(error_by_reg_and_fold) %>%
  group_by(Regression) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_MAE = round(mean(MAE), 2),
              SD_MAE = round(sd(MAE), 2)) %>%
  kable() %>%
    kable_styling(full_width = F)
Regression Mean_MAE SD_MAE
Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors 0.45 0.33
Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process 0.42 0.30
Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors 0.87 0.86
Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process 0.64 0.58

III. Generalizability by Neighborhood Context

This section uses demographic data for Chicago for the year 2018, to understand how well the model predicts weapons violations for areas that are majority white and majority non-white.

tracts18 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E"), 
          year = 2018, state=17, county=031, geometry=T) %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102271')  %>% 
  dplyr::select(variable, estimate, GEOID) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority_White", "Majority_Non_White")) %>%
  .[neighborhoods,]

ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data=tracts18, aes(fill=raceContext)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#6bb1c1","#e49100"), name= "Race Context")+
  labs(title="Race Context", 
       subtitle="Chicago, 2018\n", 
       caption="American Community Survey, 2017")+
  theme_void()

G. Kernel Density vs.Predictions

I. Kernel Width

To compare out model with a kernel density model that flattens out incidences, kernel density maps are plotted at 3 different search radii. It can be observed that in each case, there seems to be two primary hotspots for weapons violations.

G. Comparisons

I. Comparing of Kernel Density and Risk Predictions

The maps below compare the kernel density model to the risk prediction model. It can be observed that there are some overlaps in primary hotspots between both models, but the kernel density model seems to have over simplified the occurances of weapons violations, while the risk prediction model shows variation in its distribution.

II. Bar Plot

The plot below shows that our model does not predict occurrences of weapons violations better than the kernel density model in areas on either end of the risk threshold, i.e; high and low crime risk areas. It does hoewever, predict better than the kernel density model by a significant margin in areas in the 2nd and 3rd risk category. The model can definitely be improved upon by adding more spatial variables.

rbind(wepvio_KDE_sf, wepvio_risk_sf) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(countWepVio = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes = countWepVio / sum(countWepVio)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_manual(values =c("#bdc367","#ed4400") , name = "Model") +
      labs(title = "Risk prediction vs. Kernel density, 2018 burglaries",
           y = "% of Test Set Burglaries (per model)",
           x = "Risk Category") +
  theme_minimal()+ theme(legend.position="bottom")

H. Conclusion

The model created at the end of this study had a mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.42 and generalizes well across different neighborhoods. This model considered spatial risk factors like proximity to police stations, grocery stores, liquor retail stores etc. and used the k-fold cross validation method. However, it cannot be said that the model is free of bias as it seems to predict better in areas that are majority non-white, compared to areas that are majority white tracts.

When compared to the kernel density model, which seems to overlook the granular variations in occurrences of weapons violations, our model does seem to take this variations into consideration. Overall, the model from this study does show some advantages over the traditional kernel density model and can be used as a base for future predictive policing research- provided more spatial risk factors are incorporated into model. It would also be interesting to look at how occurrences of weapons violations are related to political biases- say, how do these occurrences vary in areas that are majority republican voters versus democrats.
